settings.name: Veronica
settings.popup_txt: Veronica, a mother of three and a U.S. Army veteran, describes living with PCOS as a daily challenge marked by excessive hair growth, weight gain, and fatigue. "It can be a source of embarrassment," she says, reflecting on how it affects her social interactions and self-esteem. Despite trying various treatments, including medical interventions and laser hair removal, Veronica finds managing her condition difficult, especially in her predominantly male military environment. Now, she hopes to connect with a PCOS support group and shares this message of reassurance: "You're not alone."

settings.name: Lauren
settings.popup_txt: Lauren's journey with PCOS began in high school but remained unclear until she received a formal diagnosis in 2022. The condition’s impact, particularly hirsutism, has been emotionally taxing. "It's exhausting to manage daily," she admits, describing her routine of constant shaving and the challenges of keeping her condition private. Despite these struggles, Lauren actively seeks support from dietitians and the PCOS community, aiming to raise awareness and help others. "Participating today had a lot to do with being vulnerable ... nervous ... embarrassed, [but] it's important that other women don't feel this way."

settings.name: Katie
settings.popup_txt: Katie, a 29-year-old healthcare professional, struggled with PCOS symptoms since her teens, including abnormal hair growth and inflammation. After a long journey of misdiagnoses, she finally received a PCOS diagnosis, providing some relief but also revealing ongoing challenges. "My self-perception with PCOS builds insecurity and creates doubts in my self-confidence," Katie says, noting the difficulties with unwanted hair growth and melasma. She finds comfort in a supportive community and encourages others to view their condition as a learning process: "Treat [your body] like an experiment. The more you know, the more you can help yourself and feel better."

settings.name: Morgan
settings.popup_txt: At 24, student Morgan reflects on how PCOS has influenced every aspect of her life, from relationships to self-image. Bullied in school for excess hair, she faced significant emotional challenges. "PCOS has been a curse and a blessing," she says, acknowledging how it has shaped her resilience. Despite exploring various hair removal methods, Morgan desires a reliable, painless solution. Her message to other women with PCOS is straightforward: Don’t hide from it. There’s help available. "You’re not alone out there."

settings.title: What skin and hair tones are best for Ulike IPL?
settings.answer:
Ulike IPL works best on lighter skin and darker hair tones. It targets melanin in the hair follicle, making it less effective on lighter hair or darker skin.

Please refer to the our compatibility chart before making a purchase.

settings.title: Does IPL help with PCOS-related hair growth?
settings.answer:
Yes, IPL can help manage PCOS-related hair growth by targeting hair at the root and reducing regrowth. Of course, individuals are unique and results may vary. However, consistent use following our recommended treatment schedule leads to noticeable results:

Weeks 1 to 3: 3 treatments per week

Weeks 4 to 6: 2 treatments per week

Regular Maintenance: Continue treatments once every two weeks or once a month as needed for touch-ups. Increasing frequency and/or power level can help with particularly stubborn hair.

settings.title: How does IPL work for PCOS?
settings.answer:
IPL uses intense pulsed light to target hair follicles, reducing regrowth. Light is absorbed by melanin in the hair follicle, which gets converted into heat, resulting in thinner hair regrowth. With regular treatment, IPL eventually halts hair regrowth altogether. Its effectiveness is backed by clinical studies and is FDA cleared.

For women with PCOS who may experience increased hair growth, IPL operates just as effectively as it does for those without PCOS. Unlike the constant cycle of shaving or other traditional hair removal methods that can cause pain or skin irritation, Ulike IPL devices offer a nearly painless and long-lasting solution for hair removal.

settings.title: Is IPL suitable for everyone?
settings.answer:
IPL is not recommended for individuals who

  • have certain medical conditions, including photosensitive epilepsy and cancer;
  • have skin disorders such as allergic dermatitis or eczema;
  • are menstruating, pregnant, or nursing;
  • or have sunburnt skin.

settings.title: Can I use Ulike IPL on all body parts?
settings.answer:
Ulike IPL is safe for most body areas but should be avoided on

  • the eyes or around the eyes,
  • tattoos,
  • open wounds,
  • plastic surgery,
  • and certain extra-sensitive spots like sunburns, birthmarks, moles, or warts.

settings.title: Do I need to shave before using IPL?
settings.answer: Yes, we recommend that you shave the treatment area before an IPL treatment. Shaving the hair to the appropriate length will help IPL effectively focus on the hair follicles.

settings.title: Which areas of the body can I use this on?
settings.answer:
You can use our IPL device on most areas of the body, including the Brazilian (bikini area) and face. However, do not use the device around the eyes — only treat areas below the cheekbones.

Our IPL device is not suitable for use on the inner bikini area, so avoid using it on the labia minora, vagina, scrotum, or anus.

To minimize discomfort, we recommend starting with the lowest intensity level when treating more sensitive areas, such as the bikini line, inner thighs, and buttocks.
